# Gist Thinking

Common misconceptions:

children may believe:

```text id="p6s1qe"
summary
=
retelling
everything
```

or:

```text id="u3s9qe"
supporting details
=
random facts
```

Some may:

```text id="c8s4qe"
include
opinions
instead of
text evidence
```

without understanding:

```text id="k5s7qe"
summaries
focus on
important ideas
```

Students may also think:

```text id="n1s6qe"
small details
=
main point
```

Example:

students may summarize:

```text id="t9s2qe"
article
about
rainforests
```

with:

```text id="q4s8qe"
there
was
a
green bird
```

instead of recognizing:

```text id="v7s3qe"
rainforests
support
many
living things
```

because:

```text id="a2s5qe"
summary
requires
selecting
importance
```

This skill teaches:

```text id="g8s1rx"
big-idea synthesis
```

For Grade 5:

focus includes:

Summarizing:

* gist
* concise explanation
* key events
* sequence
* central message

Supporting Details:

* evidence
* relevant information
* text structure
* fact selection
* explanation support

